1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO TAXATION; AMENDING THE DEFINITION OF "ADVANCED
3 ENERGY PRODUCT" IN THE ADVANCED ENERGY EQUIPMENT INCOME TAX
4 CREDIT AND THE ADVANCED ENERGY EQUIPMENT CORPORATE INCOME TAX
5 CREDIT.
6
7 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF NEW MEXICO:
8 SECTION 1. Section 7-2-18.39 NMSA 1978 (being Laws
9 2024, Chapter 67, Section 35) is amended to read:
10 "7-2-18.39. ADVANCED ENERGY EQUIPMENT INCOME TAX
11 CREDIT.--
12 A. The tax credit provided by this section may be
13 referred to as the "advanced energy equipment income tax
14 credit". A taxpayer who is not a dependent of another
15 individual, who makes qualified expenditures for a qualified
16 manufacturing facility located in New Mexico and who files an
17 individual New Mexico income tax return for a taxable year
18 beginning on or after January 1, 2025, and prior to January
19 1, 2033, may claim the tax credit in the amount provided in
Subsection B of this section.
20
B. The amount of the tax credit shall be in an
21
amount equal to the lesser of twenty percent of the amount of
22
the qualified expenditures made by the taxpayer for a
23
qualified manufacturing facility or twenty-five million
24
dollars ($25,000,000).
25 HB 154
Page 1

1 C. Prior to incurring a qualified expenditure, a
2 taxpayer shall apply for preliminary certification of
3 eligibility for the tax credit from the energy, minerals and
4 natural resources department on forms and in the manner
5 prescribed by that department. Such preliminary
6 certification shall be made in consultation with the economic
7 development department and shall be limited to confirming
8 that the qualified expenditures proposed to be made by the
9 taxpayer will in whole or in part be used to produce advanced
10 energy products and providing an estimate of the amount of
11 tax credit for which the taxpayer may be eligible. Only one
12 certificate of eligibility shall be issued for all activities
13 performed at a qualified manufacturing facility, regardless
14 of ownership of the facility.
15 D. Within twelve months of commencement of
16 production of any advanced energy product, the taxpayer shall
17 seek final certification from the energy, minerals and
natural resources department. The total annual aggregate
18
amount of advanced energy equipment income tax credits and
19
advanced energy equipment corporate income tax credits that
20
may be certified in a calendar year shall not exceed twenty-
21
five million dollars ($25,000,000). An application for final
22
certification shall include information required by the
23
energy, minerals and natural resources department to
24
determine eligibility for the tax credit, including
25 HB 154
Page 2

1 information substantiating qualified expenditures. If, after
2 consultation with the economic development department, the
3 energy, minerals and natural resources department determines
4 that the taxpayer meets the requirements of this section, the
5 energy, minerals and natural resources department shall issue
6 a dated certificate of eligibility to the taxpayer providing
7 the amount of tax credit for which the taxpayer is eligible
8 and the taxable years in which the credit may be claimed.
9 The energy, minerals and natural resources department shall
10 provide the department with the certificates of eligibility
11 issued pursuant to this subsection in an electronic format at
12 regularly agreed-upon intervals. A certificate of
13 eligibility for the tax credit may be sold, exchanged or
14 otherwise transferred to another taxpayer in increments of
15 not less than one million dollars ($1,000,000); provided that
16 if the total amount certified is less than one million
17 dollars ($1,000,000), the certificate of the entire amount of
the credit may be transferred. The parties to such a
18
transaction shall notify the department of the sale, exchange
19
or transfer within ten days of the sale, exchange or transfer
20
in an electronic format prescribed by the department.
21
E. A taxpayer allowed to claim the tax credit
22
shall claim the credit in a manner required by the
23
department. The tax credit shall be claimed within one year
24
of receiving final certification from the energy, minerals
25 HB 154
Page 3

1 and natural resources department. The taxpayer shall claim
2 the amount certified and approved against the taxpayer's
3 income tax liabilities. Any amount of credit that exceeds
4 the taxpayer's income tax liabilities may be carried forward
5 for five consecutive taxable years. A taxpayer who claims
6 the tax credit shall report to the department and the energy,
7 minerals and natural resources department on the continued
8 operations of the qualified manufacturing facility.
9 F. Married individuals filing separate returns for
10 a taxable year for which they could have filed a joint return
11 may each claim only one-half of the tax credit that would
12 have been claimed on a joint return.
13 G. A taxpayer may be allocated the right to claim
14 the tax credit in a proportion to the taxpayer's ownership
15 interest if the taxpayer owns an interest in a business
16 entity that is taxed for federal income tax purposes as a
17 partnership or limited liability company and that business
entity has met all of the requirements to be eligible for the
18
credit. The total credit claimed by all members of the
19
partnership or limited liability company shall not exceed the
20
allowable credit pursuant to this section.
21
H. If the taxpayer or a successor in the business
22
of the taxpayer ceases operations at the qualifying
23
manufacturing facility or ceases to produce advanced energy
24
products for at least one hundred eighty days within a two-
25 HB 154
Page 4

1 year period after the taxpayer has claimed the tax credit,
2 any amount of credit that received final certification with
3 respect to that facility that is not claimed against a
4 taxpayer's tax liability shall be extinguished, and within
5 thirty days after the one hundred eightieth day of cessation
6 of operations, the taxpayer who received final certification
7 pursuant to Subsection D of this section shall pay to the
8 department the tax liability against which the certified
9 credit was claimed. For the purposes of this section, a
10 taxpayer shall not be deemed to have ceased operations during
11 reasonable periods for maintenance or retooling, for the
12 repair or replacement of facilities damaged or destroyed or
13 during labor disputes.
14 I. The tax credit provided by this section shall
15 be included in the tax expenditure budget pursuant to Section
16 7-1-84 NMSA 1978, including the annual aggregate cost of the
17 tax credit.
J. As used in this section:
18
(1) "advanced energy product" means:
19
(a) a solar energy component, including
20
a solar module, photovoltaic cell, photovoltaic wafer, solar-
21
grade polysilicon, torque tube, structural fastener or
22
polymeric backsheet;
23
(b) a wind energy component, including
24
a wind turbine blade, nacelle and tower;
25 HB 154
Page 5

1 (c) a battery component, including an
2 electrode-active material, a battery cell and a battery
3 module;
4 (d) a fusion machine and the components
5 of a fusion machine that can transform atomic nuclei through
6 fusion processes into different elements, isotopes or other
7 particles, including associated systems essential to
8 facilitate fusion processes;
9 (e) a critical mineral, if converted or
10 purified to specified purities or forms, including aluminum,
11 antimony, arsenic, barite, bismuth, cerium, cesium, chromium,
12 cobalt, dysprosium, erbium, europium, fluorspar, gadolinium,
13 gallium, germanium, graphite, hafnium, holmium, indium,
14 iridium, lanthanum, lithium, lutetium, magnesium, manganese,
15 neodymium, nickel, niobium, palladium, platinum,
16 praseodymium, rhodium, rubidium, ruthenium, samarium,
17 tantalum, tellurium, terbium, thulium, tin, titanium,
tungsten, vanadium, ytterbium, yttrium, zinc and zirconium;
18
and
19
(f) an inverter that is an end product,
20
which is suitable to convert direct current energy from one
21
or more solar module or certified distributed wind energy
22
systems into alternating current electricity, including a
23
central inverter, commercial inverter, distributed wind
24
inverter, microinverter, residential inverter or utility
25 HB 154
Page 6

1 inverter;
2 (2) "essential" means directly necessary to
3 the production of an advanced energy product;
4 (3) "manufacturing equipment" means an
5 essential machine, mechanism or tool or a component of an
6 essential machine, mechanism or tool used directly and
7 exclusively in a taxpayer's qualified manufacturing facility
8 and that is subject to depreciation pursuant to the Internal
9 Revenue Code by the taxpayer carrying on the manufacturing.
10 "Manufacturing equipment" does not include a vehicle that
11 leaves the site of a manufacturing operation for the purpose
12 of transporting persons or property, including property for
13 which the taxpayer claims a credit pursuant to Section 7-9-79
14 NMSA 1978;
15 (4) "qualified expenditure" means an
16 expenditure made on or after January 1, 2025 and prior to
17 January 1, 2033 for the purchase of that portion of the costs
of manufacturing equipment dedicated to manufacturing
18
advanced energy products; and
19
(5) "qualified manufacturing facility" means
20
a facility located in New Mexico, including any connected,
21
associated or subsidiary facilities, that employs personnel
22
to perform production tasks with manufacturing equipment not
23
previously existing at the facility to produce advanced
24
energy products."
